{"result": {"response": {"id": "chatcmpl-E52G4d3eUQ1MiCWvcqZlzIRPvivAJ", "choices": [{"finish_reason": "stop", "index": 0, "logprobs": null, "message": {"content": "{\n  \"title\": \"NCCN Breast Cancer Protocols: Locoregional and Systemic Treatment Decision Network\",\n  \"summary\": \"This community comprises NCCN breast cancer protocol entities centered on locoregional and systemic treatment modalities, decision points for targeted patient profiles, and guideline-driven branching treatment paths. The entities range from detailed protocol steps for specific tumor and nodal statuses (e.g., BINV-2, BINV-3, BINV-5, BINV-6, BINV-8) to treatment modalities such as mastectomy types, radiation therapy (RT) options, surveillance/follow-up routines, and decision nodes for histopathology. Key relationships map treatment recommendations to patient-specific characteristics, ensuring precision in therapy assignment for HR-positive, HER2-positive, HR-negative, or triple-negative disease, as well as distinguishing favorable from less common histologic types. This protocol-driven network is highly influential in breast cancer care, affecting numerous patient management decisions and aligning clinical practice with evidence-based recommendations.\",\n  \"findings\": [\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Central Role of Locoregional Treatment Pathways (BINV-2 and BINV-3)\",\n      \"explanation\": \"BINV-2 and BINV-3 serve as foundational protocols delineating locoregional treatment options for early-stage breast cancer patients (cT1-3, cN0/cN+, M0). BINV-2 focuses on breast-conserving surgery (BCS) plus/minus RT, mapping directly to detailed recommendations on radiation therapy techniques (whole breast RT ± boost, with or without comprehensive regional nodal irradiation) and surgical staging options. BINV-3 addresses various forms of mastectomy—with or without postmastectomy radiation therapy (PMRT)—and includes further stratification based on surgical margins and nodal status. Multiple steps within these protocols demarcate subsequent branching into systemic therapy and follow-up procedures, highlighting their importance as convergence points in the decision network [Data: Entities (108, 96, 97, 109); Relationships (212, 214, 215, 216, 206, 234, 241, 242, 243, 244, 245,+more)].\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Guideline-Driven Adjuvant Systemic Therapy Triage\",\n      \"explanation\": \"The BINV-4 protocol node triages adjuvant systemic therapy decisions after surgery based on histology and receptor status. This protocol bridges to downstream regimens tailored for HR-positive/HER2-negative (BINV-6, BINV-8), HR-positive/HER2-positive (BINV-5), HR-negative/HER2-positive (BINV-9), and unfavorable triple-negative disease (BINV-10). The inclusion of a separate pathway for favorable histologies (BINV-11), such as pure tubular or mucinous carcinomas, ensures nuanced therapy adaptation aligned with evidence and risk stratification. The interconnected relationships from BINV-4 to histologic subtypes, receptor status, and further to specific adjuvant protocols reflect the protocol's pivotal role in personalized cancer care [Data: Entities (119, 137, 133, 154, 0, 151, 13, 131, 23); Relationships (264, 276, 288, 296, 321, 378, 394, 30, 0,+more)].\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Integration of Pathologic Nodal Status in Decision Points\",\n      \"explanation\": \"Pathologic (pN) status strongly influences post-surgical adjuvant treatment, particularly RT and chemotherapy recommendations. Explicit nodes for pN0/cN0, pN1a, pN2-3, and more are referenced; these dictate whether to omit RT, pursue whole breast RT ± boost, or escalate to comprehensive RT and consider PMRT. pN status also guides systemic therapy decisions and surveillance intensity. This granularity ensures that therapy is appropriately matched to disease risk, outcome probabilities, and minimizes unnecessary treatment toxicity [Data: Entities (99, 100, 101, 102, 110, 111, 112, 113); Relationships (220, 221, 223, 224, 227, 252, 254,+more)].\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Detailed Recommendations on Radiation Therapy and Surgical Margins\",\n      \"explanation\": \"Numerous protocol steps rigorously specify RT modalities, timing relative to chemotherapy, and margin management, including options like 'no RT', partial or comprehensive RNI, and re-excision for positive margins. Decisions regarding the use of PMRT are stratified by nodal positivity and margin status. The protocols reflect high-level consensus and provide both flexibility and clear categories (e.g., category 1 evidence, strong consideration for PMRT, or preferred re-excision). These details reduce variation in clinical practice and drive high-value care [Data: Entities (114, 115, 116, 117, 118, 103, 105, 106, 107); Relationships (241, 242, 243, 244, 245, 221, 224, 227, 252, 254, 256,+more)].\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Dedicated Treatment Pathways for Special Histologic Subtypes\",\n      \"explanation\": \"Certain rare histologic breast cancer types (e.g., adenoid cystic, secretory, cribriform, etc.) are mapped to distinct protocols that may favor less aggressive adjuvant therapy or altered local management, reflecting their generally favorable prognosis. These types are directly triaged to BINV-11. The presence of this distinction in the protocol network ensures clinicians are reminded to tailor interventions for these subtypes, thus avoiding overtreatment [Data: Entities (23, 131, 132, 13); Relationships (30, 54, 276, 288)].\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Structured Approach to Surveillance and Follow-up (BINV-17)\",\n      \"explanation\": \"Surveillance and follow-up protocols specify intervals for exams, imaging, genetic screening/referral, and education/management of side effects like lymphedema. There are clear steps for post-treatment monitoring, recurrence detection, and the transition to long-term survivorship care, contributing to both safety and quality of life for survivors. The branching decision nodes in these pathways lead to further management if recurrence is detected [Data: Entities (45, 46, 47, 48, 49, 50); Relationships (104, 108, 109, 110, 111, 112)].\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Emphasis on Comprehensive, Multidisciplinary Care Sequencing\",\n      \"explanation\": \"There is explicit guidance on sequencing systemic therapy, radiation, and surgical interventions. Systemic therapy may be recommended after BCS or mastectomy sequences, with RT typically given post-systemic therapy. The protocol also covers the impact of systemic therapies on complications (e.g., cardiotoxicity monitoring) and the implications for ongoing endocrine therapy and supportive care such as bone mineral density monitoring and gynecologic surveillance [Data: Entities (98, 49, 103); Relationships (219, 218, 247, 112)].\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"rating\": 9.0,\n  \"rating_explanation\": \"The protocols constitute the backbone of contemporary breast cancer management, influencing large-scale clinical practice and patient outcomes, thus posing a very high impact on health care decisions.\"\n}", "refusal": null, "role": "assistant", "annotations": [], "audio": null, "function_call": null, "tool_calls": null, "provider_specific_fields": {"refusal": null}}, "provider_specific_fields": {}}], "created": 1784869028, "model": "gpt-4.1-2025-04-14", "object": "chat.completion", "moderation": null, "service_tier": "default", "system_fingerprint": "fp_b5121c360f", "usage": {"completion_tokens": 1566, "prompt_tokens": 5668, "total_tokens": 7234, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": 0, "audio_tokens": 0, "reasoning_tokens": 0, "rejected_prediction_tokens": 0}, "prompt_tokens_details": {"audio_tokens": 0, "cache_write_tokens": null, "cached_tokens": 0}}, "formatted_response": null, "content": "{\n  \"title\": \"NCCN Breast Cancer Protocols: Locoregional and Systemic Treatment Decision Network\",\n  \"summary\": \"Th